VALUES(4548, 'Let me out.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4549, 'No.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4550, 'You can''t keep me in here!', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4551, 'I daresay I can. And if you actually do attack me with that wand, Harry, I''m afraid to say you will regret it.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4552, 'It is my fault Sirius died tonight.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4553, 'Harry, I owe you this explanation, to show you the failings of an old man.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4554, 'I already know all this.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4555, 'Haven''t you wondered why I haven''t spoken to you, even looked at you, for months?', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4556, 'Well, yeah, I did...', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4557, 'Sirius told me you believed there was a snake inside of you. This was Voldemort attempting to manipulate you. To protect you from this, I had you study Occlumency.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4558, 'But Snape stopped giving me lessons.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4559, 'Yes. I thought he could overcome his feelings towards your father, but I was wrong. Some wounds cut too deep to be healed.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4560, 'He barely taught me, though. I always felt more open to it after the lessons. Like he was trying to open me to Voldemort--', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4561, 'I would trust Severus Snape with my life, Harry. You have never recovered from your mistrust of him in your first year.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4562, 'Sirius didn''t trust him. Didn''t believe he''d really turned to our side...', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4563, 'Again, some wounds run too deep to be healed, Harry. Severus and Sirius never liked each other at school. This has never changed.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4564, 'During your Occulumency lessons, Professor Snape discovered that you were dreaming about the door in the Department of Mysteries.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4565, 'I''ve been dreaming about that all year, before Voldemort discovered the connection.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4566, 'Yes. Voldemort has been obsessed with hearing that prophesy since he returned. Because of your scar, what he was obsessed with, you were obsessed with, in the form of dreams.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4567, 'Once he discovered the connection, Voldemort had little difficulty in manipulating you into thinking he had captured Sirius.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4568, 'But I checked Grimmauld Place! Kreacher said--', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4569, 'Kreacher lied. He wanted you to go to the Department of Mysteries.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4570, 'Why?', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4571, 'Kreacher has been serving two masters for some months now.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4572, 'What?', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4573, 'Wait, where was Sirius when I tried to contact him?', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4574, 'Ah. Apparently Kreacher had injured Buckbeak to distract him in case you tried to contact Headquarters.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4575, 'Sirius was tending to the wounds when you called.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4576, 'And Hermione said we should be nice to Kreacher!', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4577, 'She was quite right, Harry. Kreacher is what wizards have made him. He is to be pitied, not hated.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4578, 'Sirius hated him.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4579, 'He didn''t hate Kreacher himself. Kreacher was a reminder to Sirius of the home he had always hated.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4580, 'Yeah, he really hated that place. And you kept him locked up in there!', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4581, 'I was trying to save his life!', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4582, 'I also knew that Voldemort would return one day. I played to his weakness. There is an ancient magic which Voldemort has always underestimated.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4583, 'This magic is what your mother gave you when she died. That protection would only work, however, if you were cared for by a blood relative. Your Aunt, Petunia.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4584, 'She never loved me.', 156, 1, 41);
VALUES(4585, 'Perhaps not. But she took you in, however grudgingly. As long as you can call your Aunt''s house your home, you are protected.', 156, 4, 41);
VALUES(4669, 'You should feel honored, Cissy. As should Draco --', 158, 22, 16);
VALUES(4586, 'And now we come to the moment of terrible truth, the moment I have dreaded for fifteen years. The moment when I must lay another burden atop your already straining shoulders.', 156, 4, 41);
